Congratulations! You just completed the third case! 

The diagnostic approach to suspected underlying cardiac disease should involve a thorough history and complete physical examination, since the symptoms are generally non-specific (cough, dyspnea, fatigue). 

The cardiac echo can aid in the diagnostic evaluation, showing left atrial dilation and pulmonary hypertension. The EKG also has an important role to play in establishing the diagnosis. 

The appropriate treatment for this patient includes diuretics to manage pulmonary edema, penicillin to prevent rheumatic fever recurrence, and a beta-blockers. Inotropes and IV fluids are not indicated and may harm the patient. 

In general, evaluation and management by a cardiologist is strongly advised in cases of mitral stenosis, since the treatment guidelines tend to be complicated. 

The next step in managing this patient is to refer her for a mitral valve intervention, as severe mitral stenosis is a potentially life-threatening condition that requires urgent treatment. 

